definition.value: Any surgery involving cutting into the hymen.

A medical procedure involving the surgical opening of the hymen. It is often performed on patients with an imperforate or septate hymen, or other situations where the hymen is unusually thick or rigid such as microperforate hymen. In the case of a person with a hymen without any opening, an opening may be created in order to facilitate menstruation. In situations where the opening is extremely small or the band(s) of a septate hymen limit access to the vaginal opening, the individual may elect for hymenotomy to allow for comfortable sexual penetration of their vagina, or to relieve pain or discomfort that occurs when inserting/removing tampons.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the epididymis.
The surgical removal of all or part of the vulva.
Surgical resection of the vulva.
Vulvectomy in which the skin and superficial subcutaneous tissues surrounding the vulva are removed.
Vulvectomy in which the skin and deep subcutaneous tissues are removed.
A simple vulvectomy in which less than 80% of the vulvar area is removed.
A simple vulvectomy in which more than 80% of the vulvar area is removed.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the prostate.

Health care services related to human reproduction and diseases of the reproductive system. Services are provided to both sexes and usually by physicians in the medical or the surgical specialties such as reproductive medicine; andrology; gynecology; obstetrics; and perinatology.
Health care programs or services designed to assist individuals in the planning of family size. Various methods of contraception can be used to control the number and timing of childbirths.
A course or method of action selected to guide and determine present and future decisions.
A plan of action adopted by an individual or social group.
Decisions for determining and guiding present and future objectives from among alternatives.
A course or method of action selected, usually by a government, from among alternatives to guide and determine present and future decisions.

A course or method of action selected, usually by a government, to guide and determine present and future decisions on population control by limiting the number of children or controlling fertility, notably through family planning and contraception within the nuclear family.
The process of bringing something into the mainstream.

Gender mainstreaming is the public policy concept of assessing the different implications for women and men of any planned policy action, including legislation and programmes, in all areas and levels.
Sex work done by migrant workers.

A venue where strip dancers provide the primary source of entertainment, predominantly in the form of striptease or other erotic dances. Strip clubs typically adopt a nightclub or bar style, and can also adopt a theatre or cabaret-style.

A variant of "yes means yes" consent is enthusiastic consent. Project Respect states that "positive sexuality" needs to start with enthusiastic consent" in which a person is as "excited and into someone elses enjoyment" a they are, an engaged partner. Planned Parenthood says that enthusiastic consent can be seen when a partner is "...happy, excited, or energized".
Consent expressed specifically, either verbally or in the form of writing.

Consent which is not expressly granted by a person, but rather implicitly granted by a person's actions and the facts and circumstances of a particular situation (or in some cases, by a person's silence or inaction). The term is most commonly encountered in the context of United States drunk driving laws. There are no U.S. states that allow implied consent as an excuse for rape in a court of law.

An institutional policy of granting authority to health personnel to perform procedures on patients or to remove organs from cadavers for transplantation unless an objection is registered by family members or by the patient prior to death. This also includes emergency care of minors without prior parental consent.
Sexual consent in which all parties agree to sexual conduct, either through clear, verbal communication or nonverbal cues or gestures.
Consent which allows a decision maker to attempt to establish the decision an incompetent person would have made if they were competent.
Consent given by all parties.

label.value: congenital malformation of the circulatory system

definition.value: Any malformation or condition related to a circulatory malformation which is present at birth, regardless of cause.
A defect in the structure of the heart or great vessels that is present at birth.
Any malformation or condition related to a heart malformation which is present at birth, regardless of cause.

label.value: congenital malformation of the nervous system

definition.value: Malformations of any part or the entirety of the nervous system which are present at birth.
Any malformation or condition related to a cerebral malformation which is present at birth, regardless of cause.

A congenital nervous system abnormality characterized by failure of the anterior neuropore to close resulting in partial or complete absence of the cranial vault accompanied by absence of overlying tissues, including the brain and cerebral hemispheres, skull and scalp.

A malformation of the nervous system caused by failure of the anterior neuropore to close. Infants are born with intact spinal cords, cerebellums, and brainstems, but lack formation of neural structures above this level. The skull is only partially formed but the eyes are usually normal. This condition may be associated with folate deficiency. Affected infants are only capable of primitive (brain stem) reflexes and usually do not survive for more than two weeks.
A rare neural tube defect during pregnancy, resulting in the absence of a large portion of the brain and skull in the fetus.

label.value: congenital malformation of the neural tube

definition.value: Congenital malformations of the central nervous system and adjacent structures related to defective neural tube closure during the first trimester of pregnancy generally occurring between days 18-29 of gestation. Ectodermal and mesodermal malformations (mainly involving the skull and vertebrae) may occur as a result of defects of neural tube closure.
An abnormal accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid within the ventricles of the brain that is present at birth.
Hydrocephalus that is present at birth.
A congenital abnormality in which the cerebrum is underdeveloped, the fontanels close prematurely, and, as a result, the head is small.

Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender. Head circumference is measured from just above the glabella (the most prominent point on the frontal bone above the root of the nose) to the most posterior prominent point of the occipital bone using a tape measure. Some standard charts are organized by centiles, others by standard deviations. It is important to add an indication of how far below the normal standard the head circumference is if an accurate assessment of this can be made. Microcephaly is an absolute term. The term relative microcephaly can be used when the head size centile is less than the centile for height, for example, head size at the 3rd centile with height at the 75% for age and sex. On prenatal ultrasound, microcephaly is diagnosed if the head circumference or the biparietal diameter is more than three standard deviations below the mean.
A congenital neural tube defect in which vertebrae are not fully formed. It results in the protrusion of the spinal cord through the opening of the vertebrae.
Incomplete closure of the embryonic neural tube, whereby some vertebral arches remain unfused and open. The mildest form is spina bifida occulta, followed by meningocele and meningomyelocele.
Malformations of any part or the entirety of the urethra which are present at birth.

A birth defect due to malformation of the urethra in which the urethral opening is above its normal location. In those with a penis, the malformed urethra generally opens on the top or the side of the penis, but the urethra can also be open the entire length of the penis. In those with a clitoris, the malformed urethral opening is often between the clitoris and the labia, or in the abdomen.
A congenital malformation in which the vagina is underdeveloped.

A feature of a statistical technique or of its results whereby the expected value of the results differs from the true underlying quantitative parameter being estimated. The bias of an estimator of a parameter should not be confused with its degree of precision as the degree of precision is a measure of the sampling error.
Personal life is the course of an individual's life, especially when viewed as the sum of personal choices contributing to one's personal identity.
Everyday life comprises the ways in which people typically act, think, and feel on a daily basis.
A sector of a person's day-to-day existence which may involve sexual activity or represent the absence of sexual activity.
A life lived during which one suppresses or ignores elements of their identity in order to belong to a particular group or subgroup, in order to conform to the expectations of others.
Any process involving law or legality.
A dispute between opposing parties which may be resolved by a court, or by some equivalent legal process.
A lawsuit or legal case involving some aspect of civil law or civil law procedure.
A legal case in which a person is tried as a criminal or which otherwise involves some aspect or aspects of criminal law.
Any of various legal cases which reach the federal level or federal courts in government.
A lawsuit or legal case involving some aspect or aspects of family law.
